The '''Harlem Globetrotters''' are an [[Exhibition game|exhibition]] [[basketball]] team. They combine [[wikt:athleticism|athleticism]], [[theater]], and [[comedy]] in their style of play. Over the years they have played more than 26,000 exhibition games in 123 countries and territories. The team's signature song is [[Brother Bones]]' whistled version of "[[Sweet Georgia Brown]]". Their mascot is an anthropomorphized globe named Globie. The team plays over 450 live events worldwide each year. The team is currently owned by [[Herschend Family Entertainment]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Company buys Harlem Globetrotters |url=http://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/9753269/harlem-globetrotters-acquired-herschend-family-entertainment-corp |website=www.espn.com}}</ref> The executive offices for the team are located in suburban Atlanta.

==History==
The Globetrotters originated on the south side of [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], in the 1920s, where all the original players were raised. The Globetrotters began as the Savoy Big Five, one of the premier attractions of the Savoy Ballroom opened in January 1928, a basketball team of African-American players that played exhibitions before dances. In 1928, several players left the team in a dispute. That autumn, several of the players, led by Tommy Brookins, formed a team called the "Globe Trotters" and toured Southern Illinois that spring. [[Abe Saperstein]] became involved with the team as its manager and promoter. By 1929, Saperstein was touring Illinois and Iowa with his basketball team called the "New York Harlem Globe Trotters". Saperstein selected [[Harlem]], [[New York City|New York]], [[New York (state)|New York]], as their home city since Harlem was considered the center of African-American culture at the time and an out-of-town team name would give the team more of a mystique.<ref name="harlem">{{cite web | last = Smith | first = Jay | title = Harlem Globetrotters | website = [[WTTW]] |publisher=Window to the World Communications Inc.| url = http://www.wttw.com/main.taf?p=1,7,1,1,18 | accessdate = December 29, 2007 }}</ref> In fact, the Globetrotters did not play in Harlem until 1968, four decades after the team's formation.

[[File:1950 World Series Harlem Globetrotters.jpg|thumb|right|250px|1950 World Series Harlem Globetrotters with owner [[Abe Saperstein]] (right) and team secretary W. S. Welch (left)]]
The Globetrotters were perennial participants in the [[World Professional Basketball Tournament]], winning it in 1940. In a heavily attended matchup a few years later, the [[1948 Globetrotters–Lakers game]], the Globetrotters made headlines when they beat one of the best white basketball teams in the country, the Minneapolis Lakers (now the [[Los Angeles Lakers]]). Once one of the most famous teams in the country, the Globetrotters were eventually eclipsed by the rise of the [[National Basketball Association]], particularly when NBA teams began fielding African-American players in the 1950s.<ref name="globe">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/07/24/books/review/24BERKOWL.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|title='Spinning the Globe': Ball Hog Heaven|first=Ira|last=Berkow|date=July 24, 2005|accessdate=May 23, 2015}}</ref> In 1950, Harlem Globetrotter [[Chuck Cooper (basketball)|Chuck Cooper]] became the first black player to be drafted in the NBA by Boston and teammate [[Nat "Sweetwater" Clifton]] became the first African-American player to sign an NBA contract when the [[New York Knicks]] purchased his contract from the Globetrotters.

The Globetrotters gradually worked comic routines into their act—a direction the team has credited to [[Goose Tatum|Reece "Goose" Tatum]],<ref>{{cite web|website=Harlem Globetrotters|url=http://www.harlemglobetrotters.com/our-story|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930215157/http://www.harlemglobetrotters.com/our-story|dead-url=yes|archive-date=September 30, 2011|title=Our Story|accessdate=May 23, 2015|df=}}</ref> who joined in 1941—and eventually became known more for entertainment than sports.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/2015/03/21/harlem-globetrotters-keeping-fun-sports/bhSDDQwz3Jl0NCcKhR9dcM/story.html |work=The Boston Globe|publisher=[[John W. Henry|Boston Globe Media Partners, LLC]]|date=March 21, 2015|accessdate=May 23, 2015|title=Harlem Globetrotters keeping the fun in sports|first=Kevin Paul|last=Dupont}}</ref> The Globetrotters' acts often feature incredible coordination and skillful handling of one or more basketballs, such as passing or juggling balls between players, balancing or spinning balls on their fingertips, and making unusually difficult shots.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.axs.com/the-harlem-globetrotters-spin-their-way-to-denver-31752| agency= AXS| first= Deb| last= Flomberg|title=The Harlem Globetrotters spin their way to Denver|date=December 6, 2014| accessdate= May 23, 2015}}</ref>

In 1952, the Globetrotters invited [[Louis Klotz|Louis "Red" Klotz]] to create a team to accompany them on their tours. This team, the [[Washington Generals]] (who also played under various other names), became the Globetrotters' primary opponents. The Generals are effectively stooges for the Globetrotters, with the Globetrotters handily defeating them in thousands of games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportsworld.nbcsports.com/washington-generals-folding-harlem-globetrotters/|title=Losers' Lament: After decades of defeat, the Washington Generals have lost for the final time|first=Joe|last=Posnanski|accessdate=August 14, 2015|work=[[NBC Sports]]|publisher=[[NBC Sports Group]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/espn/story/_/id/13433859/harlem-globetrotters-drop-washington-generals-primary-opponent|title=After 63 years, Globetrotters drop rival Generals as primary opponent|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=[[ESPN Inc.]]|date=August 14, 2015|accessdate=August 14, 2015|first=Darren|last= Rovell}}</ref>

[[File:The Harlem Globetrotters in Scheveningen.ogv|thumb|right|250px|The Harlem Globetrotters in the Netherlands (1958)]]
In 1959, the Globetrotters played nine games in Moscow after Saperstein received an invitation from Vasily Gricorevich, the director of [[Luzhniki Stadium|Lenin Central Stadium]].<ref name="Sun 16 June 1959" /> The team, which included Wilt Chamberlain, was welcomed enthusiastically by spectators and authorities; they met Premier [[Nikita Khrushchev]]<ref name="Victoria Advocate 9 July 1959">{{cite news|title=Khruschchev Surprises U.S. Cagers By Street|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yQBIAAAAIBAJ&sjid=0IAMAAAAIBAJ&dq=globetrotters%20moscow&pg=5358%2C2447599|accessdate=20 September 2012|newspaper=[[The Victoria Advocate]]|publisher=Victoria Advocate Publishing|date=July 9, 1959|agency=Associated Press|page=15}}</ref>  and collectively received the Athletic Order of Lenin medal.<ref name="Cummings 2011">{{cite news|last=Cummings|first=Richard H.|title=Harlem Globetrotters and Nikita Khrushchev|url=http://coldwarradios.blogspot.com/2011/01/harlem-globetrotters-and-nikita.html|accessdate=September 20, 2012|newspaper=Cold War Radios|date=January 30, 2011}}</ref>

However, according to one report, spectators were initially confused: "A Soviet audience of 14,000 sat almost silently, as if in awe, through the first half of the game. It warmed up slightly in the second half when it realized the Trotters are more show than competition."<ref name="Eagle 7 July 1959">{{cite news|title=Russians Baffled by Harlem Fun|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=sJAhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=-JcFAAAAIBAJ&dq=globetrotters%20moscow&pg=6190%2C2163140|accessdate=September 20, 2012|newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]]|publisher=Reading Eagle Company|date=July 7, 1959|agency=[[United Press International]]|page=3}}</ref> The Globetrotters brought their own opponent—not the Washington Generals, but the San Francisco Chinese Basketeers.<ref name="Sun 16 June 1959">{{cite news|title=Abe's 'Trotters Off to Moscow|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=YY9lAAAAIBAJ&sjid=FooNAAAAIBAJ&dq=globetrotters%20moscow&pg=3015%2C3683991|accessdate=20 September 2012|newspaper=Vancouver Sun|publisher=[[Postmedia Network]]|date=June 16, 1959|agency=Associated Press|page=16}}</ref> A review in [[Pravda]] stated, "This is not basketball; it is too full of tricks" but praised the Globetrotters' skills and suggested that "they have some techniques to show us."<ref name="Leader-Post 8 July 1959">{{cite news|title=Globetrotters impress Soviets|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=IatUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=pzsNAAAAIBAJ&dq=globetrotters%20moscow&pg=3437%2C1213817|accessdate=September 20, 2012|newspaper=[[Leader-Post]]|publisher=Postmedia Network|date=July 8, 1959|agency=Associated Press}}</ref>
The American press—particularly [[Drew Pearson (journalist)|Drew Pearson]]—made note of the fact that the Globetrotters were paid (per game) the equivalent of $4,000, which could be spent only in Moscow. The games were used as evidence that U.S.–Soviet relations were improving, that Moscow was backing off its criticism of race relations inside America, and that the USSR was becoming more capitalist (Pearson suggested that the games were held because Lenin Stadium needed money).<ref name="Pearson 1959">{{cite news|last=Pearson|first=Drew|title=US–USSR Relations Much Improved|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=BJUuAAAAIBAJ&sjid=OUgDAAAAIBAJ&dq=globetrotters%20moscow&pg=7134%2C5499922|accessdate=September 20, 2012|newspaper=[[Deseret News]]|publisher=[[Deseret Management Corporation]]|date=July 30, 1959}}</ref><ref name="Pearson 11 Sept 1959">{{cite news|last=Pearson|first=Drew|title=Ike Should Go to Russia|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=bVcrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=8JwFAAAAIBAJ&dq=globetrotters%20moscow&pg=1202%2C1724043|accessdate=September 20, 2012|newspaper=Daytona Beach Morning Journal|date=September 11, 1959|page=13}}</ref>

Many famous basketball players have played for the Globetrotters. Greats such as "Wee" Willie Gardner, [[Connie Hawkins|Connie "The Hawk" Hawkins]], [[Wilt Chamberlain|Wilt "The Stilt" Chamberlain]], and [[Nathaniel Clifton|Nat "Sweetwater" Clifton]] later went on to join the NBA. The Globetrotters signed their first female player, Olympic gold medalist [[Lynette Woodard]], in 1985.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.cleveland.com/sports/index.ssf/2008/12/globetrotters_mains.html |work= [[The Plain Dealer]]|publisher=[[Advance Publications]] |location= Cleveland |title= It's a new spin: Harlem Globetrotters trying to put a high-tech gleam on a vintage product |date= December 22, 2008 |first= Bill |last= Lubinger |accessdate= May 23, 2015}}</ref> The Globetrotters have featured thirteen female players in their history. Baseball Hall of Famers Ernie Banks, Bob Gibson, and Ferguson Jenkins also played for the team at one time or another. 
Because the majority of the team players have historically been [[African American]], and as a result of the  buffoonery involved in many of the Globetrotters' [[sketch comedy|skit]]s, they drew some criticism during the [[Civil Rights]] era. The players were accused by some civil-rights advocates of "Tomming for Abe", a reference to [[Uncle Tom]] and Jewish owner [[Abe Saperstein]]. However, prominent civil rights activist [[Jesse Jackson]] (who would later be named an Honorary Globetrotter) came to their defense by stating,
"I think they've been a positive influence... They did not show blacks as stupid. On the contrary, they were shown as superior."<ref name="globe"/>
In 1995, Orlando Antigua became the first Hispanic player on the team. He was the first non-black player on the Globetrotters' roster since Bob Karstens played with the squad in 1942–43.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/12/28/sports/sports-people-basketball-a-non-black-player-joins-globetrotters.html|title=Sports People: Basketball – A Non-Black Player Joins Globetrotters|date=December 28, 1995|work=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times Company|access-date=July 6, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>

While parts of a modern exhibition game are pre-planned, the games themselves are not fixed. While their opponents do not interfere with the Globetrotters’ hijinks while on defense, they play a serious game when in possession of the ball and about 20 to 30 percent of a game is "real". This once led to an infamous defeat at the hands of the Washington Generals, to the distress of a watching crowd.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sportsgrid.com/basketball-3/as-the-harlem-globetrotters-ditch-their-archrivals-we-remember-the-one-time-the-washington-generals-won/|title=Washington Generals Beat Harlem Globetrotters|date=August 14, 2015|work=SportsGrid|access-date=July 6, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>

==Trophies==
The Globetrotters won the [[World Professional Basketball Tournament]] once, in 1940, beating the [[Chicago Bruins]] with a score of 31–29.

